did.abstract: The papers consist of correspondence, diaries, notebooks, school notes, and other papers of O.C. Marsh, scientist and first professor of paleontology at Yale and in the United States. Of special interest is the rather extensive correspondence Marsh carried on with many prominent scientists of his time; included are letters from Charles Darwin, Leonard and Thomas Huxley, Simon Newcomb, and Benjamin Silliman Sr. and Jr. Also included are materials relating to Marsh's education at Andover, Yale, and in Germany, family papers, and papers reflecting his involvement with the Cardiff Giant hoax and the Red Cloud controversy.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Othniel Charles Marsh, born in Lockport, New York, in 1831, was the son of Caleb and Mary Peabody Marsh. When he was three years old his mother died of cholera, and thereafter her bachelor brother, George Peabody, assumed full financial responsibility for Othniel's education at Andover, Yale (class of 1860), and in Germany. When he returned to Yale in 1865, Marsh was appointed the first professor of paleontology in the western hemisphere and influenced his uncle, George Peabody, to provide funds for the construction of a Natural History Museum at Yale. While searching for fossils in the western states, Marsh's discoveries included an extinct bird with teeth and eighty new forms of dinosaurs. These won him acclaim at home and in Europe. Owing to the death at mid-term of the president of the National Academy of Science, Marsh became acting president from 1880-1883. He was then elected president for two successive six-year terms, filling that office for longer than any previous or subsequent incumbent. Marsh devoted so much of his inherited fortune to the collecting of specimens for Yale that at the end of his life he found himself forced to mortgage his Prospect Street home in New Haven. Never having married, he named Yale his sole beneficiary, but his estate amounted to very little, except for the $18,694 realized when the contents of his home were auctioned in New York. Marsh died in his New Haven home from pneumonia on March 18, 1899.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The papers consist of correspondence, diaries, notebooks, school notes, and other papers of O.C. Marsh, scientist and first professor of paleontology at Yale and in the United States. Of special interest is the rather extensive correspondence Marsh carried on with many prominent scientists of his time; included are letters from Charles Darwin, Leonard and Thomas Huxley, Simon Newcomb, and Benjamin Silliman Sr. and Jr. Also included are materials relating to Marsh's education at Andover, Yale, and in Germany, family papers, and papers reflecting his involvement with the Cardiff Giant hoax and the Red Cloud controversy.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged in seven series and one addition: I. Correspondence. II. Marsh Family. III. Education of O. C. Marsh. IV. Writings of O. C. Marsh. V. Biographical Information. VI. Cardiff Giant Hoax. VII. Red Cloud Agency.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The general correspondence, previously housed at the Peabody Museum, is predominantly scientific in nature. There are more than twelve thousand items, beginning with letters written to and from Marsh following his return from Germany in 1865 and continuing until his death in 1899. Among the socially and scientifically prominent correspondents represented are Cleveland Abbe; Alexander and Louis Agassiz; Spencer Baird; Phineas Barnum; Albert Bierstadt; George Jarvis Brush; William Fredrick Cody; James Dwight Dana; Charles Darwin; Ulysses S. Grant; Asa Gray; Joseph Henry; Ferdinand Hayden; Leonard and Thomas Huxley; Simon Newcomb; Benjamin Silliman, Sr. and Jr.; Herbert Spencer; and Eli Whitney. Relatively few of Marsh's own letters have survived, except for occasional rough drafts that he retained. After the advent of the typewriter, however, his side of the correspondence is represented more frequently.

The most voluminous correspondence is with his co-workers and "bonediggers" such as C. E. and M. P. Felch, George Bird Grinnell, John B. Hatcher, Arthur Lakes, Benjamin F. Mudge, Samuel W. Williston, and W. H. Reed. When each specimen was received in New Haven, it was assigned an identifying number, which was also inscribed within a parallelogram on the accompanying letter or letters.

Marsh's fossil collecting reached its peak in the 1870s and 1880s. His autocratic disposition led to difficulties with some of his colleagues. His lifelong rivalry with Edward C. Cope, who was his junior by nine years and who also aspired to the presidency of the National Academy of Science but was never elected, was a discredit to both men. Their quarrel is sparsely documented in the correspondence, except for an exchange of letters in 1873. There is also an excerpt from a letter written in December of the same year by one of Marsh's loyal diggers, announcing that Cope had inspected Marsh territory and that Davendorf "... discovered marks distinclty made, I presume, by Cope, so I judged he could strike certain places next spring. These marks are now defaced by the sole of my boot, but I know where they are."

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The family materials are divided into "Family correspondence" and "Special files." The former is arranged alphabetically by the last name of the writer and family correspondents include Marsh, his grandfather, father, mother, stepmother, aunts, uncles, and sisters. The "Special files" contain family material other than correspondence--including memorabilia, legal papers, property inventories, receipts, photographs, copybooks, and newsclippings--and are arranged by specific family member.The earliest family letter is dated fourteen years before Othniel's birth, and his mother's special file Also included in the family correspondence are letters from Marsh to his uncle, George Peabody, and others, referencing the projected Peabody Museum at Yale, and memorabilia of Marsh's German sojourn. From the date of his appointment to the chair of paleontology at Yale in 1865 until his death, Marsh received no salary, presumably because it was expected that he would be one of George Peabody's heirs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials documenting Marsh's education include early school catalogues, receipts, prayer books, autographs, and his Yale notebooks on chemistry, geology, and meteorology. The series also contains his Berlin notes on zoology and paleontology and his Breslau notes on echinoderms and geognosie, song books from Yale and Heidelberg, and his passport, letter of credit, and German diplomas.

scopecontent.p: Marsh's writings include unpublished materials, such as diaries, notebooks, and compositions written at Andover and Yale.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The biographical material in this series includes five chapters of Marsh's projected autobiography, begun the year before his death and known as his "Narrative Volume." One chapter of this unfinished work, condensed in the Schuchert-Le Vene biography, provides a vivid account of a buffalo hunt when Marsh was caught on muleback in a stampeding herd. Also included are letters between Ernest Howe and George Bird Grinnell and between Howe and Schuchert concerning biographies of Marsh, a 1940 exchange between George F. Eaton and J. Donald Adams of the New York Times , and an album of obituary clippings on Marsh.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Material relating to the Cardiff Giant Hoax of 1869, which kept recurring in the news until 1918. Marsh was always skeptical. He was asked in 1869 to authenticate the giant, and concluded that the alleged giant was no fossil, but a hand-carved sculpture that had been buried in Onondaga County, New York, so that it might be exhumed in an attempt to deceive the public.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials documenting the Red Cloud Agency controversy, precipitated by Marsh after he had personally observed how the local agents of the Bureau of Indian Affairs issued short and shoddy rations to their charges. By calling attention to these corrupt practices, Marsh won the enmity of certain Washington bureaucrats and politicians. Marsh's crusade garnered strong editorial and public support, and Red Cloud visited New Haven to thank Marsh in person. Included in this series are the essential government reports and publications pertaining to the controversy, as well as correspondence (arranged chronologically) for the period from 1873-1876, plus a few items dated later. Among the many letters congratulating Marsh on his exposure of these scandals, Thaddeus H. Stanton wrote succinctly on June 19, 1875: "Go after the thieves, old boy, and make it hot for 'em." Additional references to the Red Cloud controversy can be found in Series I. General Correspondence, in folders for the following: Charles H. Denison, Ulysses S. Grant, Red Cloud, Thaddeus H. Stanton, and Wiliam Welsh.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The accession comprises stereographs from O.C. Marsh's 1873 expedition to the western United States. The photographs depict primarily conditions in camp, and include one labeled Camp of the Dacotas that appears to have been taken and commercially distributed by W. H. Jacoby.
